    Kolkata beckons….

    March 1, 2016

    |

    Vinodha

    There is something inexplicably beautiful about the coastal areas of our country, with the rains enlivening these places. The greenery brings back fond childhood memories of splattering water, colorful raincoats, cutesy umbrellas, gum boots, singing in the rain, and a million other good things. I am a Mumbai girl who has been stuck up in a dry weathered city for several years now. So an invitation from my husband (my then 'good friend') to his sister’s (my now sister-in-law) wedding was just an excuse to visit Kolkata during the rains.
     

    The Singature Yellow Taxi of Kolkata

     Image Source: www.inc42.com


    The entire city is always bustling with activity…...food, colour, culture, arts, romance….these precisely are their daily pursuits. Amidst the maddening traffic, you will find people living a completely different life. Learning an art form is a default here. Kids are being educated on literature, music, fine arts, drama and cinema, rather than coding, developing, managing and likes.

    Rabindranath Tagore 

    Image Source: www.britannica.com


    Rabindranath Tagore, fondly known in this part of the country as Rabi Da, is their God. His music still echoes in the by-lanes of the city, soft, meaningful, soulful expressions in words. Pick up any true Bengali and ask him/her what they find most synonymous to Kolkata, and without a batting an eyelid, the answer would be 'Arts' (in its various forms). My visits to this place have been frequent ever since I got married, thanks to my husband who is a Bengali. Recently at a Film Festival, I got a chance to watch a few Bengali movies which belonged to the intellectual genre and hence could not be categorised under mainstream cinema. Having watched the work of Oscar winning director, Satyajit Ray, these movies were rather disturbing. And, it was difficult to accept such darkness in their films.
     

    Satyajit Ray

    Image Source: www.theguardian.com


    My husband’s grandfather (Dulal Dutta) was a very famous film editor of his times, having been a personal favourite of Mr. Satyajit Ray himself, he was the sole editor of Pather Panchali. So apart from being surrounded by Bengalis, I can boast of a historic lineage now. Pride overtakes!!

    So much is said and done about the art and culture of this place but surprisingly only a little is mentioned about the food. Kolkata is not only limited to Rasgullas and Sandesh, but in fact, I don't think there is a limit at all!
     

    A colonial era building in the New Market of Kolkata

    Image Source: www.livemint.com


    Street food rocks at rock bottom prices! My first encounter was outside New Market where I had a plate of chicken momos with chicken clear soup for only Rs. 25/-, and no, it wasn’t sub-standard. It tasted as good as the momos I have had at a good Chinese restaurant. Chaat lovers can also have a feast here. Although, I ain’t a big fan but have noticed so much of variety here, Jhaal Muri being their favourite and possibly the most famous worldwide.
     

    Jhaal Muri

    Image Source: www.worldofmoms.com


    I am inseparable from coastal food and hence, I love the fact that quite a lot of coconut is used in Bengali cuisine. Chingri malai curry (Prawns in coconut gravy) deserves a special mention for its subtle flavors and the richness of coconut cream, making it the most delectable food item.

     

    Chingri Macher Malai Curry

    Image Source: www.amchibong.wordpress.com


    While talking about food, one cannot miss THE ROLLS! My favourite joint is the one at Gariahat Market that offers rolls with fillings of fish, mutton, chicken, egg, paneer, vegetables and prawns in Mughlai and Bengali style at unbeatable prices. So, if you are in Kolkata, the rolls are a must have! You can comfortably survive gorging on these sumptuous rolls. Apart from momos, you get our Indian-style chowmein that is available in every nook and corner of the city.

    Kolkata Chicken Roll

    Image Source: www.sharmilazkitchen.com 


    Bengali food is incomplete without talking about two very important food items - Fish and Sweets. I remember my husband sharing his experience of staying in Kolkata for 3 months when he was a bachelor and lived with his relatives. So the story starts at 8:00 AM when he used to start for work. He had to walk about 10 minutes to reach the nearest bus stop and on his way were 5 sweet shops. He would stop at each one, have a different variety of sweet and then board the next bus to office. The afternoon meal would comprise of rice and fish curry for a meagre Rs. 20/- with a different variety fish every day of the week!

    Sweets displayed in a Sweet Shop at Kolkata

    Image Source: www.topyaps.com


     

    Ilishi Maachha

    Image Source: www.pinterest.com


    Returning home would mean stopping at the very same sweet shops once again. He says, “Else, it wouldn’t do justice to my evening craving for sweets” LOL!!! That’s how a Bengali describes his love for fish and sweets.


    One thing no woman can talk enough about nor stop at is Shopping! Its is sheer pleasure and Kolkata has plenty to offer on the shopping front. The best places to shop are Gariahat Market, New Market, Burrabazar Market, Park Street (not many are aware of the oldest shop selling original leather products at dirt cheap rates), and College Stree. Sarees are a must buy when at Gariahat Market. I am not recommending any particular shop here as they all are equally good, selling the best quality clothes, jewellery, footwear, knick-knacks, and souvenirs also. Buy as much as you want, and trust me if you can, it will NOT pinch your pocket!
     

    An array of junk jewellery available at the Kolkata New Market

    Image Source: www.flickr.com


    Every time I am there, I shop like it is the end of the world. Terracotta jewellery I understand is quite a in trend these days, bringing out the ethnic side of a woman. These are available at any of the markets I have mentioned above. I have found fantastic junk jewellery at New Market and around it, the kinds which are so expensive in other cities.

    Trending stuff seems to appear very quickly in the markets of Kolkata as the people are very fashionable and like to stay so. Bengali women, whoa!…..so beautiful with lovely Kohl-lined eyes, always turned out in their best look. There is enough to shop for men too, they can splurge on the ethnic kurtas and chappals.

    Whether it is the magic of rains or how Kolkata really is, it’s difficult to tell. Monsoons are the best time to visit this place. Just take a stroll in the Victoria Memorial premises and you will know what I am talking about. Walk on the grass barefoot, feel the misty air, droplets of rain on your face, the cool breeze and cherish all these in the presence of the soothing silence, which we sadly miss in our daily lives.

     

    Victoria Memorial at Kolkata

    Image Source: www.expedia.com
